      <body>
			<div type="edition" xml:lang="pyx-Latn">
				<ab>
					<lb n="1"/>
					
							<unclear>t</unclear>ga
					siri
					<!-- MM2AG: not sure if I have encoded Middleton's two readings properly. -->
					<!-- AG2MM: probably need to use <choice>; then perhaps apply n="1" and n="2" on first and second <rdg>? -->
					<!-- MM2AG: following was rejected:
                    <choice><rdg source="#Middleton2005" n="1">sibi</rdg> <rdg source="#Middleton2005" n="2">sidha</rdg></choice>
                    I couldn't find an obvious model for choice and readings by a specified source online or in my EpiDoc class materials.
                    Could you please add the choice tags and n-values?
                    -->
				</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="apparatus">
				<listApp>
					<app loc="1">
						<lem><unclear>t</unclear>ga</lem>
						<note>Could be <seg type="graphemic">nga</seg>.</note>
					</app>
					<app loc="2">
						<lem>siri</lem>
						<note>We read <seg type="graphemic">ri</seg>rather than <seg type="graphemic">dhi</seg> here; the loop on the akṣara is large, making it look like <seg type="graphemic">dh</seg>, but the serif of an <seg type="graphemic">r</seg> is still visible. Note same shape of <seg type="graphemic">ri</seg> in PYU 8.1.</note>
					</app>
				<app loc="1">
						<lem>
							<unclear>t</unclear>ga</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Middleton2005_01">nga</rdg>
					</app><app loc="1">
						<lem>siri</lem>
						<rdg source="bib:Middleton2005_01">sibi</rdg>
						<rdg source="bib:Middleton2005_01">sidha</rdg>
					</app></listApp>
			</div>
			<div type="translation" xml:lang="eng">
				<p>U San Win, Daw Le Le Win and Daw Sanda-U in Middleton (2005: 173)</p>
				<ab>auspicious city (nagara thiri)</ab>
			</div>
			<div type="commentary">
				<p>Middleton's statement that the inscription is in Pali is incorrect.</p>
				<p>Is the text complete, or should we indicate that the beginning and end are missing?</p>
			</div>
			<div type="bibliography">
				<!--Middleton 2005: 173 (App.58).-->
				<!--[Todo: markup citedRange elements if necessary]-->
				<p>Reported in <bibl><ptr target="bib:Middleton2005_01"/><citedRange>173-4 (App. 58)</citedRange></bibl>, thought incorrectly reported as Pali in Pyu script instead of Pyu (in Pyu script). Middleton gives three possible readings: <seg type="graphemic">nagara thiri</seg> (auspicious city), <seg type="graphemic">ngasibi</seg> or <seg type="graphemic">ngasidha</seg>; but we read <seg type="graphemic">tga siri</seg> instead. Re-edited here from a published photograph.</p>
				<!-- <listBibl type="secondary-bibliography">
				</listBibl> -->
			<listBibl type="primary"><bibl><ptr target="bib:CPI2018_01"/><citedRange unit="item">DHARMA_INSPYU00034</citedRange></bibl></listBibl></div>
